<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="4" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1324,1559,1905]" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">
Diagnosis. This species is similar in appearance to 
<taxonomicName authority="Falkovitsh" authorityName="Falkovitsh" box="[860,1176,1559,1585]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Ancylis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amplimacula">
<emphasis box="[860,1045,1559,1584]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">A. amplimacula</emphasis>
Falkovitsh
</taxonomicName>
but is easily distinguished by the paler subapical patch of the forewing and the long antrum, which constitutes the posterior 1/3 of the ductus bursae of the female genitalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1324,1559,1905]" pageId="4" pageNumber="21">
Re­description. Adult: Wingspan 
<quantity box="[720,806,1679,1705]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="21" unit="mm" value="16.0">16 mm</quantity>
in female. Forewing with costa curved at base then arched towards apex, strongly arched basally, becoming gently arched apically; ground color white; basal patch dark brown, fairly broad, covering 1/3 of forewing; subapical patch indistinct, light brown; apical spot reddish brown, very small, with characteristic tiny, black, subapical costal spot. Hindwing light brown, slightly darker in outer area; cilia long, grayish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[264,1323,284,470]" pageId="5" pageNumber="22">
Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[526,616,284,310]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1636,1660]" captionTargetBox="[488,1107,556,1598]" captionTargetId="figure-119@5.[393,1219,531,1630]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Female genitalia: 14. Ancylis melanostigma K.; 15. A. partitana (C.); 16. A. repandana K.; 17. A. upupana (T.)." pageId="5" pageNumber="22">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
): Papillae anales slender, long. Apophyses anteriores twice as long as apophyses posteriors. Ostium bursae with antrum trumpet­shaped, representing posterior 1/3 of ductus bursae. Ductus bursae moderately long, approximately the same length as corpus bursae; ductus seminalis originating from middle of ductus bursae. Corpus bursae ovate with two, large, different­sized signa.
</paragraph>
